'''Maruyama Sakura''' (丸山 作楽, [[:en:Tenpō|1840]] 11th year  {{ill|October 3 (old calendar)|ja|10月3日 (旧暦)|1=October 3 (Lunisolar)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/October 3 (old calendar)|13=User:Immanuelle/October 3 (Lunisolar)|qq=}} – [[August 19]], [[1899]]) was a [[Meiji period]] [[diplomat]], [[businessman]], and [[politician]]. He was also known by the names Masatora, Masamichi, and Sakura. His titles included Shinsūsho, Sokō, and Iwanoya. His wife's name was Umekichi (Okutsuki).

== Career ==
Maruyama was born in Edo’s Shiba Mita district as the eldest son of Maruyama Masanao, a samurai of the [[:en:Shimabara Domain|Shimabara Domain]]. During the late Edo period, he studied [[:en:Kokugaku|Kokugaku]] of the [[:en:Hirata Atsutane|Hirata Atsutane]] school and became active in the royalist movement.

In [[1869]] (Meiji 2), he became [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Japan)|Daisuke]] and was dispatched to [[:en:Sakhalin|Karafuto]] to engage in negotiations with Russia. Returning in [[1870]] (Meiji 3), he advocated an aggressive policy against Russian expansion, but his proposals were not adopted. He also supported {{ill|Sada Hakaru|ja|佐田白茅|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sada Hakaru|qq=}}’s [[:en:Seikanron|Seikanron]] and urged its implementation, but this too was rejected. In November of the same year, he was reassigned to {{ill|Ken-Daisuke (Ministry of Foreign Affairs)|ja|外務権大丞|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ken-Daisuke (Ministry of Foreign Affairs)|qq=}} due to the failure of the Karafuto negotiations.

Maruyama, along with {{ill|Hatake Kiyotada|ja|畑経世|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hatake Kiyotada|qq=}}, a samurai of the [[:en:Sasayama Domain|Sasayama Domain]], attempted to carry out the rejected Seikanron through rebellion. However, in [[1871]] (Meiji 4), their plans were uncovered, and Maruyama was arrested on [[May 10]] while on duty at the Ministry of Foreign Affairs. On [[May 29]], he was dismissed from his position as Ken-Daisuke. The incident, considered politically minor, led to his sentencing to life imprisonment. He was released in [[1880]] (Meiji 13) through amnesty.

After his release, Maruyama opposed the [[:en:Freedom and People's Rights Movement|Freedom and People's Rights Movement]] by establishing the {{ill|Chūaisha|ja|忠愛社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chūaisha|qq=}} and publishing the newspaper {{ill|Meiji Nippo|ja|明治日報|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji Nippo|qq=}}. In [[1882]] (Meiji 15), he co-founded the [[:en:Rikken Teiseitō|Rikken Teiseitō]] with [[:en:Fukuchi Gen'ichirō|Fukuchi Gen'ichirō]] and worked as a conservative politician.

In [[1890]] (Meiji 23), he was appointed {{ill|Gikanin|ja|元老院議官|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gikanin|qq=}} on [[June 12]] and became {{ill|Non-working official|ja|非職|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Non-working official|qq=}} when the [[:en:Senate|Gikan]] was abolished on [[October 20]]. He was subsequently named {{ill|Imperial appointee to the House of Peers|ja|貴族院勅選議員|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Imperial appointee to the House of Peers|qq=}} on [[September 29]], serving until his death on [[August 19]], [[1899]], due to valvular heart disease.

Maruyama was also known as a [[:en:Man'yōshū|Manyōshū]]-style poet.

== Honors ==
; Rank
* [[June 19]], [[1890]] (Meiji 23): [[Jūshi-i]]<ref>『官報』第2094号「叙任及辞令」1890th year 6月24日。</ref>

; Medals
* [[November 29]], [[1889]] (Meiji 22): {{ill|Constitution Promulgation Medal|ja|記念章#賞勲局所管の記念章|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Constitution Promulgation Medal|qq=}}<ref>『官報』第1935号「叙任及辞令」1889th year 12月9日。</ref>

