Maruyama, along with {{ill|Hatake Kiyotada|ja|畑経世|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hatake Kiyotada|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, a samurai of the [[:en:Sasayama Domain|Sasayama Domain]], attempted to carry out the rejected Seikanron through rebellion. However, in [[1871]] (Meiji 4), their plans were uncovered, and Maruyama was arrested on [[May 10]] while on duty at the Ministry of Foreign Affairs. On [[May 29]], he was dismissed from his position as Ken-Daisuke. The incident, considered politically minor, led to his sentencing to life imprisonment. He was released in [[1880]] (Meiji 13) through amnesty.

After his release, Maruyama opposed the [[:en:Freedom and People's Rights Movement|Freedom and People's Rights Movement]] by establishing the {{ill|Chūaisha|ja|忠愛社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chūaisha|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} and publishing the newspaper {{ill|Meiji Nippo|ja|明治日報|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji Nippo|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}. In [[1882]] (Meiji 15), he co-founded the [[:en:Rikken Teiseitō|Rikken Teiseitō]] with [[:en:Fukuchi Gen'ichirō|Fukuchi Gen'ichirō]] and worked as a conservative politician.

In [[1890]] (Meiji 23), he was appointed {{ill|Gikanin|ja|元老院議官|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gikanin|qq=}} on [[June 12]] and became {{ill|Non-working official|ja|非職|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Non-working official|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 分限処分}} when the [[:en:Senate|Gikan]] was abolished on [[October 20]]. He was subsequently named {{ill|Imperial appointee to the House of Peers|ja|貴族院勅選議員|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Imperial appointee to the House of Peers|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 貴族院 (日本)}} on [[September 29]], serving until his death on [[August 19]], [[1899]], due to valvular heart disease.

Maruyama was also known as a [[:en:Man'yōshū|Manyōshū]]-style poet.

