'''Maruyama Sakura''' (丸山 作楽, {{ill|Tenpō|en|Tenpō|qid=Q1369045|lt=1840|1=Tenpō}} 11th year  {{ill|October 3 (old calendar)|ja|10月3日 (旧暦)|1=October 3 (Lunisolar)|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/October 3 (old calendar)|13=User:Immanuelle/October 3 (Lunisolar)|qq=}} – {{ill|August 19|en|August 19|qid=Q2829|lt=August 19|1=August 19}}, {{ill|1899|en|1899|qid=Q7851|lt=1899|1=1899}}) was a {{ill|Meiji era|en|Meiji era|qid=Q3125096|lt=Meiji era|1=Meiji era}} {{ill|Diplomat|en|Diplomat|qid=Q193391|lt=Diplomat|1=Diplomat}}, [[:en:Businessman|Businessman]], and {{ill|Politician|en|Politician|qid=Q82955|lt=Politician|1=Politician}}. He was also known by the names Masatora, Masamichi, and Sakura. His titles included Shinsūsho, Sokō, and Iwanoya. His wife's name was Umekichi (Okutsuki).

== Career ==
Maruyama was born in Edo’s Shiba Mita district as the eldest son of Maruyama Masanao, a samurai of the {{ill|Shimabara Domain|en|Shimabara Domain|qid=Q1067706|lt=Shimabara Domain|1=Shimabara Domain}}. During the late Edo period, he studied {{ill|Kokugaku|en|Kokugaku|qid=Q855159|lt=Kokugaku|1=Kokugaku}} of the {{ill|Hirata Atsutane|en|Hirata Atsutane|qid=Q2572749|lt=Hirata Atsutane|1=Hirata Atsutane}} school and became active in the royalist movement.

In {{ill|1869|en|1869|qid=Q7720|lt=1869|1=1869}} (Meiji 2), he became {{ill|Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Japan)|en|Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Japan)|qid=Q222241|lt=Daisuke|1=Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Japan)}} and was dispatched to {{ill|Sakhalin|en|Sakhalin|qid=Q7792|lt=Karafuto|1=Sakhalin}} to engage in negotiations with Russia. Returning in {{ill|1870|en|1870|qid=Q7741|lt=1870|1=1870}} (Meiji 3), he advocated an aggressive policy against Russian expansion, but his proposals were not adopted. He also supported {{ill|Sada Hakaru|ja|佐田白茅|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sada Hakaru|1=Sada Hakubō|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11248151}}’s {{ill|Seikanron|en|Seikanron|qid=Q370290|lt=Seikanron|1=Seikanron}} and urged its implementation, but this too was rejected. In November of the same year, he was reassigned to {{ill|Ken-Daisuke (Ministry of Foreign Affairs)|ja|外務権大丞|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ken-Daisuke (Ministry of Foreign Affairs)|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} due to the failure of the Karafuto negotiations.

Maruyama, along with {{ill|Hatake Kiyotada|ja|畑経世|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hatake Kiyotada|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, a samurai of the {{ill|Sasayama Domain|en|Sasayama Domain|qid=Q3034520|lt=Sasayama Domain|1=Sasayama Domain}}, attempted to carry out the rejected Seikanron through rebellion. However, in {{ill|1871|en|1871|qid=Q7746|lt=1871|1=1871}} (Meiji 4), their plans were uncovered, and Maruyama was arrested on {{ill|May 10|en|May 10|qid=Q2557|lt=May 10|1=May 10}} while on duty at the Ministry of Foreign Affairs. On {{ill|May 29|en|May 29|qid=Q2589|lt=May 29|1=May 29}}, he was dismissed from his position as Ken-Daisuke. The incident, considered politically minor, led to his sentencing to life imprisonment. He was released in {{ill|1880|en|1880|qid=Q7806|lt=1880|1=1880}} (Meiji 13) through amnesty.

After his release, Maruyama opposed the {{ill|Freedom and People's Rights Movement|en|Freedom and People's Rights Movement|qid=Q711511|lt=Freedom and People's Rights Movement|1=Freedom and People's Rights Movement}} by establishing the {{ill|Chūaisha|ja|忠愛社|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chūaisha|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} and publishing the newspaper {{ill|Meiji Nippo|ja|明治日報|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji Nippo|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}. In {{ill|1882|en|1882|qid=Q7812|lt=1882|1=1882}} (Meiji 15), he co-founded the {{ill|Rikken Teiseitō|en|Rikken Teiseitō|qid=Q3132503|lt=Rikken Teiseitō|1=Rikken Teiseitō}} with {{ill|Fukuchi Gen'ichirō|en|Fukuchi Gen'ichirō|qid=Q861241|lt=Fukuchi Gen'ichirō|1=Fukuchi Gen'ichirō}} and worked as a conservative politician.

In {{ill|1890|en|1890|qid=Q7832|lt=1890|1=1890}} (Meiji 23), he was appointed {{ill|Gikanin|ja|元老院議官|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gikanin|1=member of the Genrōin|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11388041}} on {{ill|June 12|en|June 12|qid=Q2619|lt=June 12|1=June 12}} and became {{ill|Non-working official|ja|非職|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Non-working official|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 分限処分|1=Q11396170|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11396170}} when the {{ill|Senate|en|Senate|qid=Q2570643|lt=Gikan|1=Senate}} was abolished on {{ill|October 20|en|October 20|qid=Q2959|lt=October 20|1=October 20}}. He was subsequently named {{ill|Imperial appointee to the House of Peers|ja|貴族院勅選議員|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Imperial appointee to the House of Peers|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 貴族院 (日本)|1=House of Peers (Japan)|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q715139}} on {{ill|September 29|en|September 29|qid=Q2882|lt=September 29|1=September 29}}, serving until his death on {{ill|August 19|en|August 19|qid=Q2829|lt=August 19|1=August 19}}, {{ill|1899|en|1899|qid=Q7851|lt=1899|1=1899}}, due to valvular heart disease.

Maruyama was also known as a {{ill|Man'yōshū|en|Man'yōshū|qid=Q834321|lt=Manyōshū|1=Man'yōshū}}-style poet.

